congVote.dailyDigestCategory1: Searching for and Cutting Regulations that are Unnecessarily Burdensome Act
congVote.dailyDigestSummary: The House passed H.R. 998, to provide for the establishment of a process for the review of rules and sets of rules, by a recorded vote of 240 ayes to 185 noes, Roll No. 114. Consideration began yesterday, February 28th.<P/>Rejected the Raskin motion to recommit the bill to the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform with instructions to report the same back to the House forthwith with an amendment, by a recorded vote of 190 ayes to 235 noes, Roll No. 113.<P/>Bonamici amendment (No. 9 printed in H. Rept. 115-20) that sought to exempt any rule or set of rules relating to Title I of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965 from the provisions of this Act;<P/>Bonamici amendment (No. 8 printed in H. Rept. 115-20) that sought to exempt any rule or set of rules prescribed by the Secretary of Education and relating to consumer protections for student loan borrowers from the provisions of this Act (by a recorded vote of 191 ayes to 235 noes, Roll No. 109);

congVote.result: So the motion to recommit was rejected.

congVote.dailyDigestSummary: The House passed H.R. 1009, to amend title 44, United States Code, to require the Administrator of the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs to review regulations, by a yea-and-nay vote of 241 yeas to 184 nays, Roll No. 120.<P/>Rejected Cartwright the motion to recommit the bill to the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform with instructions to report the same back to the House forthwith with an amendment, by a recorded vote of 193 ayes to 234 noes, Roll No. 119.<P/>Pursuant to the Rule, an amendment in the nature of a substitute consisting of the text of Rules Committee Print 115-4 shall be considered as an original bill for the purpose of amendment under the five-minute rule.<P/>Connolly amendment (No. 6 printed in part B of H. Rept. 115-21) that sought to exempt independent agencies from the legislation (by a recorded vote of 188 ayes to 234 noes, Roll No. 118).<P/>H. Res. 156, the rule providing for consideration of the bills (H.R. 1004) and (H.R. 1009) was agreed to by a recorded vote of 234 ayes to 180 noes, Roll No. 116, after the previous question was ordered by a yea-and-nay vote of 233 yeas to 189 nays, Roll No. 115.

congVote.result: So the resolution was agreed to.
